column2: Master of Data Science and Analytics
Science, Haskayne School of Business and Cumming School of Medicine
Master of Data Science and Analytics

A distinctive feature of the MDSA is the ability of students to complete it on a part-time basis, and to ladder into it through the Graduate Certificate in Fundamental Data Science and Analytics and/or the Graduate Diploma in Data Science and Analytics. Students who complete the Graduate Certificate and who are subsequently accepted into the MDSA will receive 12 units of advanced credit towards the master’s degree. Students who complete the Graduate Diploma program and who are subsequently accepted into the MDSA will receive 24 units of advanced credit towards the master’s.

column1: ---------- Course: DATA 601   Working with Data and Visualization ----------

column2: Use programmatic tools and suitable programming paradigms to clean and transform data into a format suitable for subsequent analytics
Use existing software libraries to summarize and aggregate structured data
Use existing software libraries to explore data and create informative and engaging data visualizations
Present data stories in an interactive and collaborative data science environment
Apply various laws of probability to solve practical problems
Differentiate between probability models and their applications
Visualize data (univariate) that is both categorical and numerical
Carry out various manipulations of data to create deeper data visualizations
Employ both simulation and conventional methods to create confidence intervals
Employ hypothesis testing to create and critique a statistical claim
Investigate the synergy between two variables by using data visualization and various statistical tools

column1: ---------- Course: DATA 603   Statistical Modeling with Data ----------

column2: Use statistical software R to model the multiple linear relationship between a response variable (Y) and all explanatory variables (both categorical and numerical variable) with interaction terms. Interpret model parameter estimates, construct confidence intervals for regression coefficients, evaluate model fits by (R2adj and RMSE). Once the fitted model exists, predict the response variable at a certain level of the explanatory variables.

Visualize correlations between a response variable (Y) and all explanatory variables (X) by graphs (scatter plot, residual plot) to assess model validity. Check the multi -linearity problem of a MLR model, check all assumptions by residual plots and statistical tests (testing for non constant variance, testing for normality) and outliers.
Be able to use Stepwise/Forward/Backward variable selection procedures to identify the most significant subset of predictor variables that contribute to the explanation of the variation Y.
Apply transformations (logarithmic transformations, power functions) to some/all of the response variable and the predictor variables to create a better model.

Use open data set to build the best fitted model, participate in group to report for a research project. Deliver professional presentations and discuss group research project results with the entire class.

Use R software to model the logistic regression for a binary response variable with a set of independent variables (both categorical and numerical variable), interpret model parameter estimates in terms of odd ratio, construct confidence intervals for logistic regression coefficients. Predict the probability of response variable P(Y=1|X) at a certain level of the explanatory variables
Visualize correlations between a response variable (Y) and all explanatory variables (X) by graphs. Check all necessary assumptions by residual plots, multicollinearity and outliers.
Be able to locate different in methods of sampling from population and definitions of Design of Experiment

Apply the methods to test for difference in averages between levels for one factor design (complete randomized design), block design, two factor factorial design and nested design, use pairwise comparison procedures for comparing in pairs to determine which means are different from others, discuss the output in class and make conclusions.

column1: ---------- Course: DATA 604   Working with Data At Scale ----------
---------- Course: DATA 605   Actionable Visualization and Analytics ----------

column2: Visualization Types. Students should be aware of a variety of specific domain areas in information visualization such as text visualization, tree and network visualization, maps, multidimensional data visualization, physical visualization, and casual/personal visualization.
Visualization Assessment. Students should be able to interpret, critique, and deconstruct visualizations created by others.
Exploratory Data Analysis. Students should be able to conduct exploratory data analysis on real, complex data sets by creating new visualizations in  tools like Tableau and Jupyter.
Presentation. Students should be able to create visual presentations of their analytic results, including dashboards, graphical reports, presentations, and stories.

Data and Ethics. Students should be aware of the ethical implications of data collection and analytics. Students should be able to identify problematic data collection and experimentation practices, anonymize datasets, and describe good data security practices.

column1: ---------- Course: DATA 606   Statistical Methods in Data Science ----------

column2: Students finishing this course successfully are expected to have learned when the following methods may be applied, how to apply them, and how to properly interpret the results: Design of surveys and data collection.
